-      <h1>🧭 Pilot Memo™ – Dissociated Governance</h1>
-      <section id="dissociation-interne">
-        <h2>Structural leverage: internal dissociation</h2>
-
-        <p>
-          The business was
-          <mark style="background-color: #e0e0e0">legally founded by</mark>
-          <a
-            href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1JzldjCyp20MhsVrmH6PQNsqPkHcXEtvL/view?usp=sharing"
-            class="pilot-link"
-            >a single individual</a
-          >. However,
-          <mark style="background-color: #e0e0e0"
-            >operational structure and concept design</mark
-          >
-          are widely attributed to a second figure — broadly seen as the site’s
-          public face and creator of its organizational identity.
-        </p>
-
-        <section id="governance-constraints">
-          <p>
-            ⚠️ Early governance was shaped under constraint. The branding figure
-            faced unresolved liabilities — including Skatteverket — that
-            structurally barred formal registration under their name.
-          </p>
-
-          <p>
-            Legal control was likely assigned to a <u>proxy founder</u> to
-            enable licensing and compliance —
-            <mark style="background-color: #e0e0e0"
-              >a workaround aligned with standard practices</mark
-            >
-            in similar financial risk contexts.
-          </p>
-        </section>
-
-        <section id="absence-of-role">
-          <p>
-            Two figures jointly oversee <u>day-to-day operations</u>. One of
-            them — commonly identified as the <u>informal cofounder</u> —
-            remains legally invisible and detached from core operational tasks.
-          </p>
-          <p>
-            The <u>legal cofounder</u>, despite holding sole legal authority
-            over the business, <em>has not been seen interacting</em> with
-            either staff or his operational counterpart.
-          </p>
-        </section>
-
-        <section id="operational-figure">
-          <p>
-            The active operational figure is the legal cofounder's partner:
-            without any formal title, she handles onboarding, scheduling, and de
-            facto HR, with no documented delegation line.
-          </p>
-          <p>
-            In practice, she delegates heavily to a triad of N–1 figures —
-            <mark style="background-color: #e0e0e0"
-              >floor manager, bar manager, sous-chefs, and the head chef</mark
-            >
-            — for daily coordination, deliberately bypassing direct interaction
-            with the wider team.
-          </p>
-        </section>
-
-        <section id="presence-and-coordination">
-          <p>
-            While both engage intensively during those shifts, their appearances
-            appeared irregular and uncoordinated
-            <em>from the author’s vantage point</em>
-            — no visible coordination, joint appearance, or witnessed
-            communication was observed over a 3-week period.
-          </p>
-          <p>
-            Whether this absence of joint presence stems from scheduling
-            constraints or a deliberate operating model
-            <em>remains undocumented</em>.
-          </p>
-        </section>
-
-        <section id="ownership-structure">
-          <p>
-            Neither of the two figures handling day-to-day operations (informal
-            cofounder and legal cofounder's partner) is responsible for site
-            closures; opening duties remain unverified.
-          </p>
-
-          <p>
-            The majority beneficial owner (50–75%) is the informal founder's
-            partner, who remains off-site and has no known involvement while the
-            legal cofounder holds only a minority share (&lt;25%)
-          </p>
-        </section>
-
-        <section id="strategic-fragility">
-          <p>
-            <mark style="background-color: #e0e0e0"
-              >Governance relies on undocumented, non-transferable interpersonal
-              balances.</mark
-            >
-          </p>
-          <p>
-            The disconnection between economic control, active governance, and
-            legal liability creates an immediate risk of strategic dilution.
-          </p>
-        </section>
