-        <section id="riskmap">
-          <section id="legal-risks">
-            <h2>Legal Risks</h2>
-
-            <ul>
-              <li id="R01L">
-                <strong>R01L</strong> — No Written Contract, Fragmented
-                Registry, and Delayed Registration
-                <strong>[Sub-angles: R01o, R01s]</strong><br /><br />
-
-                → <u>Verbal initiation only</u>: no contract issuance at
-                start.<br />
-                🔻 <strong>Exposure to requalification</strong>: Status as
-                “svartjobb” (undeclared work), retroactive taxation,
-                Skatteverket liabilities. <br /><br />→
-                <u>Absence of onboarding protocol</u>: no documented scope of
-                duties or supervision chain.<br />
-                🔻 <strong>Procedural ambiguity </strong>: potential
-                misattribution of liability in case of incident or internal
-                complaint.<br />
-                🔻 <strong> R01s – Structural vulnerability </strong>: creates
-                space for informal performance evaluations without
-                safeguards.<br />
-                🔻 <strong> R01p – Psychological exposure </strong> : implicit
-                testing during probation period — employee left to define
-                workload, often overproducing by default under unspoken
-                evaluation. Generates anxiety, distrust, and false expectations
-                of scope clarity. <br />
-                <br />→ <u>Delayed registry input</u>: late integration into
-                staff systems (e.g., PersonalKollen).<br />
-                🔻 <strong>Administrative lag</strong>: evidentiary vacuum used
-                to delay or suppress labor protections. <br /><br />→
-                <u>Retroactive payslips</u>: no shift-level granularity or
-                timestamped entries.<br />
-                🔻 <strong>Remuneration opacity</strong>: weakens employee
-                claims, opens window for systemic concealment.
-              </li>
-              <br />
-              <li>
-                <strong>R02L</strong> — Exposure to formal labor complaints
-                <strong>[Sub-angles: R02p]</strong>
-                <br />
-                <p>
-                  ➝ Unpaid hours: informal shift extensions or undocumented
-                  overtime.<br />
-                  → Irregular work conditions: <br />
-                  🔻
-                  <strong>Psychosocial retaliation spiral resentment: </strong>
-                  latent sabotage, targeted social exposure, informal HR
-                  harassment, peer influence, revenge behaviors, premature
-                  resignation, reputational drift, turnover chain reaction.<br /><br />
-                  →
-                  <u>Unpaid hours and blurred rest periods</u>: staff silently
-                  compensates for managerial failures or design flaws. <br />🔻
-                  <strong>R02p – Psychological erosion</strong>: normalized
-                  overwork, self-silencing, fatigue accumulation, silent
-                  resentment.
-                  <br />
-                  <br />
-
-                  → <u>Formal escalation paths</u>: complaint filing, legal
-                  counsel engagement, union referral, internal reporting to
-                  hotel management, formal notice. <br />
-
-                  🔻 <strong>Legal dispute exposure</strong>: confrontation
-                  loops (emails, legal letters, mediation), loss of control,
-                  reputational spillover. <br /><br />
-                  →
-                  <u>Reputation and litigation triggers</u>: negative reviews,
-                  audit activation, public escalations, or sector press
-                  coverage. <br />🔻
-                  <strong>R02p – Public image degradation</strong>: reputational
-                  damage, executive-level scrutiny, or investor distrust.
-                  <br /><br />
-                  → <u>Night or weekend isolation</u>: preference for off-hours
-                  to avoid noise, oversight, or gossip exposure. <br />🔻
-                  <strong>R02p – Symbolic downgrade</strong>: informal
-                  exclusion, lack of recognition, perceived illegitimacy.
-                  <br /><br />
-                  → <u>Ambiguous worker status</u>: tolerated presence without
-                  proper registration or ID. <br />🔻
-                  <strong>Surveillance and micro-sanctions</strong>: informal
-                  control, rumor propagation, inequality of treatment.
-                  <br /><br />
-
-                  <strong>R02L</strong> — Exposure to formal labor complaints
-                  <strong>[Sub-angles: R02s, R02o, R02p, R02g]</strong
-                  ><br /><br />
-
-                  → Redirected or blocked escalation channels
-                  <span style="color: gray">(internal justice breakdown)</span
-                  ><br />
-                  🔻 <strong> R02s – Trust collapse</strong>: internal
-                  escalation deemed futile, bypassing official HR tracks. Breeds
-                  frustration, informal coordination, and external legal
-                  routes.<br /><br />
-
-                  → False resignation records
-                  <span style="color: gray">(legal trace manipulation)</span
-                  ><br />
-                  🔻 <strong>R02o — Legal trace distortion</strong>: undermines
-                  complaint legitimacy, delays recourse, increases risk of
-                  retroactive claims or class actions.<br /><br />
-
-                  → Administrative retaliation
-                  <span style="color: gray">(reputational backlash)</span><br />
-                  🔻 <strong>R02p — Retaliation chilling effect</strong>: staff
-                  hesitates to speak, toxic silence, delayed reporting, erosion
-                  of psychological safety.<br /><br />
-
-                  → Silenced formal complaint
-                  <span style="color: gray">(proof of HR opacity)</span><br />
-                  🔻 <strong>R02o — Opacity-induced drift</strong>: missed
-                  governance alarms, perception of impunity, chain reaction of
-                  passive resistance or moral disengagement.<br /><br />
-
-                  → Cross-entity escalation
-                  <span style="color: gray">(governance dilution)</span><br />
-                  🔻 <strong>R02g — Loss of internal authority</strong>:
-                  internal resolution blocked, leading to union contact,
-                  external legal counsel, or parent company exposure.
-                </p>
-              </li>
-
-              <li>
-                [R03L]
-                <strong
-                  >Risk of labor requalification via outsourced roles</strong
-                ><br />
-                → External kitchen or cleaning staff may be operating under
-                conditions that imply concealed employment (false freelancing or
-                shadow payroll)
-              </li>
-            </ul>
-          </section>
-
-          <h3>2. Operational</h3>
-          <ul>
-            <li id="R01O">
-              <strong>R01o</strong> — Operational Disruption via Unbounded Task
-              Design and Shift Ambiguity<br />
-              <strong>[<u>R01L</u>] </strong><br /><br />
-
-              → <u>Lack of clear shift boundaries</u>: undefined task limits,
-              unclear ending times, improvisation in closure routines.<br />
-              🔻 <strong>Operational fatigue</strong> → early resignation
-              without feedback loop.<br /><br />
-
-              → <u>Structural opacity in workload assignment</u>: early overload
-              appears pre-positioned — rationalized by presumed resilience,
-              downtime, or unchecked delegation in absence of supervision.<br />
-              🔻
-              <strong
-                >Silent demotivation + escalation of micro-conflicts</strong
-              >
-              into system-wide inefficiency.<br /><br />
-
-              → <u>Role expectations not documented</u>: new entrants lack
-              clarity on authorized scope of action or legitimate complaints.<br />
-              🔻 <strong>Breach of protocol</strong> → untraceable errors,
-              growing culture of blame dilution.<br /><br />
-
-              → <u>Informal scheduling practices</u> increase friction, reduce
-              trust, and mask potential covert labor dynamics.<br />
-
-              🔻 <strong>Undeclared labor suspicion</strong> → labor inspection,
-              potential requalification threat.<br /><br />
-            </li>
-
-            <li>
-              <strong>No designated authority on-site</strong><br />
-              → Dead zones: no one can decide, everyone can deflect
-            </li>
-            <li>
-              <strong>Dependence on informal intermediaries</strong><br />
-              → Decision flows through personal trust, not documented procedures
-            </li>
-            <li>
-              <strong>Uncontrolled sub-delegation</strong><br />
-              → Critical tasks are handed off with no feedback loop or
-              accountability
-            </li>
-            <li>
-              <strong>Risk of perpetuating detached leadership culture</strong
-              ><br />
-              → Quan requires on-site, ownership-driven leadership. Recruiting
-              figures who reproduce the prior model — delegative, intermittently
-              present, or emotionally disengaged — would reinstall the same
-              governance void that led to current instabilities. The role
-              demands high personal investment, daily operational presence, and
-              entrepreneurial posture, not staff-level detachment.
-            </li>
-          </ul>
-
-          <h3>3. Reputational</h3>
-          <ul>
-            <li>
-              <strong>Perceived integration into Elite Hotels structure</strong
-              ><br />
-              → Despite the absence of formal logos on uniforms or direct email
-              branding, the restaurant operates fully within the Elite Esplanade
-              Hotel premises.<br />
-              → For most clients and external observers, the distinction between
-              Quan and the Elite group is non-obvious. This creates reputational
-              exposure in case of incident or legal escalation.
-            </li>
-            <li>
-              <strong>Narrative leakage likely</strong><br />
-              → Without internal framing, external storytelling will take over
-            </li>
-          </ul>
-
